{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"sourceId":"chanakyaNiti","displayName":"Chanakya Niti","version":"1.0","language":"English","edition":"Wikiquote & Public Domain","primaryCategory":"Philosophy & Wisdom","subcategory":"Ancient Indian","type":"quotes","browseOrder":"sequence","supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true,"groupingLevels":[],"sortPriority":42,"languageCode":"en","displayNameEnglish":"Chanakya Niti","script":"Latin","isRTL":false,"transliterationAvailable":false,"contentRating":"general","audienceTags":["tradition:hindu","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","audience:inspiration"],"itemCount":118,"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Chanakya_Niti.json"},"data":[{"id":"chanakya-0001","text":"If a king is energetic, his subjects will be equally energetic. If he is reckless, they will not only be reckless likewise, but also eat into his works. Besides, a reckless king will easily fall into the hands of his enemies. Hence the king shall ever be wakeful.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0002","text":"All urgent calls he shall hear at once, but never put off; for when postponed, they will prove too hard or impossible to accomplish.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0003","text":"The king who is situated anywhere immediately on the circumference of the conqueror's territory is termed the enemy.The king who is likewise situated close to the enemy, but separated from the conqueror only by the enemy, is termed the friend (of the conqueror).","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0004","text":"The area extending from the Himalayas in the north to the sea and a thousand yojanas wide from east to west is the area of operation of the King-Emperor.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0005","text":"Ravana, unwilling under the influence of vanity to restore a stranger's wife, as well as Duryodhana to part with a portion of his kingdom.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0006","text":"Don't judge the future of a person based on his present conditions, because time has the power to change black coal to shiny diamond.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0007","text":"A person should not be too honest. Straight trees are cut first and honest people are screwed first.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0008","text":"Till the enemy's weakness is known , he should be kept on friendly terms.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0009","text":"Our bodies are perishable, wealth is not at all permanent and death is always nearby. Therefore we must immediately engage in acts of merit.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0010","text":"The serpent, the king, the tiger, the stinging wasp, the small child, the dog owned by other people, and the fool: these seven ought not to be awakened from sleep.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0011","text":"Skills are called hidden treasure as they save like a mother in a foreign country.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0012","text":"The world's biggest power is the youth and beauty of a woman.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0013","text":"Treat your kid like a darling for the first five years. For the next five years, scold them. By the time they turn sixteen, treat them like a friend. Your grown up children are your best friends.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0014","text":"Lakshmi, the Goddess of wealth, comes of Her own accord where fools are not respected, grain is well stored up, and the husband and wife do not quarrel.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:god"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0015","text":"There is no disease so destructive as lust.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0016","text":"The wise man should restrain his senses like the crane and accomplish his purpose with due knowledge of his place, time and ability.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:knowledge"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0017","text":"We should always speak what would please the man of whom we expect a favour, like the hunter who sings sweetly when he desires to shoot a deer.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0018","text":"It is better to live under a tree in a jungle inhabited by tigers and elephants, to maintain oneself in such a place with ripe fruits and spring water, to lie down on grass and to wear the ragged barks of trees than to live amongst one's relations when reduced to poverty.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:self"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":true,"verificationNote":"Verified from English Wikiquote page."},{"id":"chanakya-0019","text":"A person should not be too honest. Straight trees are cut first and honest people are screwed first.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0020","text":"Before you start some work, always ask yourself three questions — Why am I doing it, What the results might be and Will I be successful. Only when you think deeply and find satisfactory answers to these questions, go ahead.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:self"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0021","text":"The biggest guru-mantra is: never share your secrets with anybody. It will destroy you.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0022","text":"A man is great by deeds, not by birth.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0023","text":"Once you start a working on something, don't be afraid of failure and don't abandon it. People who work sincerely are the happiest.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0024","text":"The fragrance of flowers spreads only in the direction of the wind. But the goodness of a person spreads in all directions.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0025","text":"Whores don't live in company of poor men, citizens never support a weak company and birds don't build nests on a tree that doesn't bear fruits.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0026","text":"God is not present in idols. Your feelings are your god. The soul is your temple.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:soul","theme:god"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0027","text":"Learn from the mistakes of others. You can't live long enough to make them all yourself.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:self"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0028","text":"A good wife is one who serves her husband in the morning like a mother, loves him in the day like a sister and pleases him like a prostitute at night.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:love"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0029","text":"Books are as useful to a stupid person as a mirror is useful to a blind person.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0030","text":"Treat your kid like a darling for the first five years. For the next five years, scold them. By the time they turn sixteen, treat them like a friend. Your grown up children are your best friends.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0031","text":"Education is the best friend. An educated person is respected everywhere. Education beats beauty and youth.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0032","text":"He who is overly attached to his family members experiences fear and sorrow, for the root of all grief is attachment. Thus one should discard attachment to be happy.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:courage"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0033","text":"There is some self-interest behind every friendship. There is no friendship without self-interests. This is a bitter truth.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:truth","theme:self"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0034","text":"As soon as the fear approaches near, attack and destroy it.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:courage"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0035","text":"Even if a snake is not poisonous, it should pretend to be venomous.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0036","text":"The one excellent thing that can be learned from a lion is that whatever a man intends doing should be done by him with a whole-hearted and strenuous effort.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0037","text":"Never make friends with people who are above or below you in status. Such friendships will never give you any happiness.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0038","text":"Do not put your trust in rivers, men who carry weapons, beasts with claws or horns, women, and members of a royal family.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0039","text":"As long as your body is healthy and under control and death is distant, try to save your soul; when death is imminent what can you do?","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:soul"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0040","text":"The earth is supported by the power of truth; it is the power of truth that makes the sun shine and the winds blow; indeed all things rest upon truth.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:truth"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0041","text":"Those base men who speak of the secret faults of others destroy themselves like serpents that stray onto ant hills.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0042","text":"There is no disease so destructive as lust; no enemy like infatuation; no fire like wrath; and no happiness like spiritual knowledge.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:knowledge"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0043","text":"O wise man! Give your wealth only to the worthy and never to others. The water of the sea received by the clouds is always sweet.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0044","text":"Accumulated wealth is saved by spending just as incoming water is saved by letting out stagnant water.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0045","text":"He who has wealth has friends and relations; he alone survives and is respected as a man.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0046","text":"Test a servant while in the discharge of his duty, a relative in difficulty, a friend in adversity, and a wife in misfortune.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:duty"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0047","text":"Happiness is given not by wealth, not by friends, not by beauty; it is available to the man in whose heart lives wisdom.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0048","text":"A man who has not studied the scriptures, who does not love his wife, and who is ignorant of the world around him might as well be dead.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:love"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0049","text":"Do not reveal what you have thought upon doing, but by wise counsel keep it secret, being determined to carry it into execution.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0050","text":"We should not fret for what is past, nor should we be anxious about the future; men of discernment deal only with the present moment.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0051","text":"The life of an uneducated man is as useless as the tail of a dog which neither covers its rear end nor protects it from the bites of insects.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0052","text":"The serpent, the king, the tiger, the stinging wasp, the small child, the dog owned by other people, and the fool: these seven ought not to be awakened from sleep.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0053","text":"Conceal your purpose like a tree keeping its new buds covered. When the time is ripe, show your glory and strength.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:strength"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0054","text":"He who gives up shyness in monetary dealings, in acquiring knowledge, in eating and in business, becomes happy.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:knowledge"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0055","text":"That man is truly wise who is prepared for every eventuality.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0056","text":"One who is in search of knowledge should give up the search for pleasure, and one who is in search of pleasure should give up the search for knowledge.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:knowledge"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0057","text":"Know the enemy's strength, your own strength, and compare the two carefully before you venture into battle.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:strength"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0058","text":"Skill is knowing how to use the available means to achieve a desired end.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0059","text":"The ruler who shows kindness to those who deserve punishment and punishes those who deserve kindness, brings suffering to himself and his kingdom.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:self"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0060","text":"Never reveal what you have thought upon doing. Keep your plans secret as the seed in the ground, and let them be seen by the world only after they have sprouted and grown.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0061","text":"Be it in the forest, or in the palace, be it in the sea or the sky, the power of knowledge protects the knowledgeable one.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:knowledge"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0062","text":"Work brings greater happiness than idleness.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0063","text":"Let not a single day pass without your learning a verse, half a verse, or a fourth of it, or even one letter of it; nor without attending to charity, study, and other pious activity.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0064","text":"By following the pure knowledge revealed by the great souls, let people regulate their life.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:soul","theme:knowledge"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0065","text":"Whoever is overly attached to money or to desire will face destruction, for money alone does not lead to happiness.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0066","text":"Whatever is consistent with right reason is to be adopted even if it comes from a child; whatever is inconsistent with it is to be rejected even if it comes from an old man or even from the great sage.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0067","text":"The strength of a man who remains calm and silent is the greatest strength of all.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:strength"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0068","text":"As a single withered tree, if set fire to, causes a whole forest to burn, so does a rascal son destroy a whole family.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0069","text":"Even a pandit comes to grief by giving instruction to a foolish disciple, by maintaining a wicked wife, and by excessive familiarity with the miserable.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0070","text":"From the cowardice of those who refuse to engage in war springs the boldness of the enemy.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0071","text":"The qualities of the mind, which arise from past actions, are not perceptible in a person who is in the beginning of anything.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:mind","theme:action"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0072","text":"Speak not the truth to the unrighteous, for lies in that case are far better. As when a fowler sets a net to capture birds, the net is concealed by blades of grass, so a wise man conceals his truth.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:truth"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0073","text":"The person who by cultivating good qualities has already conquered his inward enemies — greed, vanity, passion — conquers the external enemy too.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0074","text":"Be always careful about the beginning of a work: the success depends on the right start.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0075","text":"Do not let your teeth be seen when you are arguing with someone: it shows a lack of dignity.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0076","text":"The pleasure which we obtain from external sources is happiness mixed with pain. True happiness comes from within.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0077","text":"The great strength of a king lies in his army, of a monarch's in his treasure, of a brahmin in his knowledge, and of a simple man in his humility.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:knowledge","theme:strength"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0078","text":"He who masters learning when young thrives as an adult; uneducated, he cannot enjoy the pleasures of life.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0079","text":"Excess of love and excess of gold ruin everything, as a kite is brought down by rain of excessive force.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:love"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0080","text":"The tree laden with fruits bows its head; so a man of great knowledge and wisdom stays humble.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:knowledge"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0081","text":"A king without wisdom is like a kingdom without righteousness.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0082","text":"When you are very faithful and true, you conquer the hearts of people.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0083","text":"The man who is wealthy but miserly will be deserted by all.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0084","text":"Those who work hard and save wisely shall succeed.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0085","text":"Do not speak what is unpleasant, speak what is true and what is pleasing.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0086","text":"The wise regard the world as a tree upon which all human beings are fruit and flowers.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0087","text":"As fire is the gold's refinement, so is adversity the testing of man's resolve.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0088","text":"Never feel complacent in the face of danger and never feel frightened in the face of fortune.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0089","text":"Power should reside where capability resides.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0090","text":"When counsel is lacking, a king with a bad army will always fail.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0091","text":"The wise man who makes happiness his goal will never be without it.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0092","text":"Never trust in a greedy man; for greed is never satisfied and the greedy man ruins all around him.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0093","text":"As one can ascertain the depth of a well by throwing a pebble, so one can gauge the depth of a man's character by testing him with hardship.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0094","text":"There is nothing in this world that is truly pure. The mind alone, purified by discipline, becomes pure.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:mind"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0095","text":"One who burns with the fire of desire will be consumed by it. One who extinguishes desire through wisdom will shine eternally.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0096","text":"The flower blossoms when it is ready, not before; wisdom too blossoms only when the mind has been properly cultivated.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:mind"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0097","text":"A man's intentions reveal his character; more revealing than his words.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0098","text":"Rely not on the king's mercy, for a king's pleasure and displeasure both bring sorrow.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0099","text":"Modesty is the adornment of women; patience the adornment of the wise; forgiveness the adornment of the great.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0100","text":"Before you make a king of any person, learn his character thoroughly by living with him.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0101","text":"A wise man shall make himself lord of his senses and, having vanquished them, shall then conquer others.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:self"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0102","text":"Self-discipline is the mother of all good qualities.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:self"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0103","text":"As a bird cannot fly without wings, a man cannot achieve his goals without acquiring the necessary qualities.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0104","text":"He who wields the sword of knowledge fears neither the enemy nor death.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:knowledge","theme:courage"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0105","text":"A king who rules without wisdom shall fall; and a man who acts without knowledge shall fail.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:knowledge"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0106","text":"Wisdom is acquired not by years but by study and reflection.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0107","text":"He who is modest and gentle, who overcomes evil through good, who turns strife into friendship — that person is great.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0108","text":"Better a single drop of the right action than an ocean of the wrong kind.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:action"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0109","text":"The man who does not strive, does not pray, does not seek counsel, does not reflect — he shall never be free from the chain of birth and death.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0110","text":"The wise learn more from one moment of deep silence than from a lifetime of argument.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0111","text":"He who speaks the truth, who speaks with sweetness, who acts for the welfare of all — in that person virtue and prosperity reside together.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:truth"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0112","text":"The four gifts of heaven are: a noble wife, a dutiful son, a king who gives protection, and a time of prosperity.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0113","text":"One must not put his trust in superficial appearances.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0114","text":"As the potter shapes clay to useful ends, so the wise man shapes his life to virtue.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0115","text":"Never waste a moment; time, once passed, cannot be recalled.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0116","text":"The truly wise man neither desires praise nor fears censure.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:courage"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0117","text":"He who learns from every encounter — good or bad — becomes a master of life.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."},{"id":"chanakya-0118","text":"There is no poverty for the diligent; no sin for the japa-meditator; no fear for the truthful; no misery for the generous.","author":"Chanakya","source":"Chanakya Niti Shastra (traditional; public domain)","tags":["tradition:hindu","language:en","theme:wisdom","theme:leadership","theme:ethics","theme:strategy","audience:inspiration","theme:truth","theme:courage"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Traditional Chanakya Niti aphorism; exact source text varies across recensions."}]}